1
00:00:02,932 --> 00:00:10,404
Finding yourself some quiet place to sit comfortably for about 45 minutes for this Vipassana meditation practice.

2
00:00:10,425 --> 00:00:16,954
And making sure your clothing is loose and comfortable, switching off your mobile phone or anything else you can do to help yourself relax.

3
00:00:19,158 --> 00:00:26,088
The guidance given here is according to the technique developed by the Mahasi Sayadaw of Burma, known as the Mahasi Method.

4
00:00:29,748 --> 00:00:36,968
We are letting go of all our usual busyness and taking time to relax, sit still and notice what this actually feels like.

5
00:00:38,171 --> 00:00:44,770
Sometimes it may feel like a relief and then after a while we might get fed up and want something more active to do.

6
00:00:44,750 --> 00:00:51,878
The challenge is to take an interest in both experiences, the sense of relief and the feeling of being fed up.

7
00:00:51,898 --> 00:00:53,619
It's the same for whatever comes our way.

8
00:00:53,679 --> 00:01:04,612
Deep peace, disturbing noises, happiness, sleepiness, itchy toes, heavenly bliss, cold hands are just plain old matter-of-fact ordinariness.

9
00:01:05,534 --> 00:01:08,596
We get to know the moment-to-moment feeling of all of these.

10
00:01:10,045 --> 00:01:17,914
We're spending time getting in touch with the moment to moment feeling of our life, the raw data, so to speak, that comes into our senses each moment.

11
00:01:19,295 --> 00:01:24,260
So we get to know ourselves and the world we live in at a deeper, more basic level in this practice.

12
00:01:25,462 --> 00:01:27,623
This knowledge is of itself healing.

13
00:01:28,364 --> 00:01:36,694
And when we know the world around us and the world within us at the deepest possible level, we will come into total harmony, compassion and peace.

14
00:01:38,445 --> 00:01:46,055
For the present though, our job is to stay awake, to relax as best we can, while also maintaining an interest in our various experiences.

15
00:01:49,721 --> 00:01:55,487
See if you can find a way of sitting comfortably, while also having your back straight, as this helps you to be more alert.

16
00:01:56,969 --> 00:02:04,099
You might imagine a puppet string attached to the crown of your head, tugging your head and neck gently upwards towards the ceiling.

17
00:02:05,159 --> 00:02:07,902
And your chin might drop a little as your neck lengthens.

18
00:02:08,862 --> 00:02:12,986
And the upward pull lifts each bone in the spine, so you're sitting upright.

19
00:02:16,411 --> 00:02:22,317
And all the rest of the body can relax, as if you are a puppet, just dangling on the end of that puppet string.

20
00:02:24,157 --> 00:02:25,400
Your face can relax.

21
00:02:26,180 --> 00:02:32,567
Your eyes can close gently, or if you prefer, keeping the eyes slightly open, but gazing downwards towards the floor.

22
00:02:34,521 --> 00:02:43,216
your shoulders relaxing, and the arms falling from the shoulders, falling down to the hands which are resting comfortably in your lap.

23
00:02:44,598 --> 00:02:46,882
Traditionally, the right hand rests in the left.

24
00:02:49,125 --> 00:03:01,525
The chest can relax, and the waist, and the stomach, abdomen, pelvis, all softening, relaxing.

25
00:03:03,614 --> 00:03:14,183
You might feel yourself sitting down more heavily into the cushion or chair and your hips loosening a little as all the muscles lose tension, soften and relax.

26
00:03:14,204 --> 00:03:18,929
The muscles of the thighs as well, not having to bear your weight now so they can take it easy.

27
00:03:18,968 --> 00:03:26,597
And your knees also, as if the upper and lower legs are only loosely bound at the knees.

28
00:03:28,459 --> 00:03:32,962
The lower legs can relax as well, falling loosely into the ankles.

29
00:03:34,342 --> 00:03:37,366
And the feet as if they were falling out of the ankles.

30
00:03:38,848 --> 00:03:41,491
And the toes as if they're just falling out of the feet.

31
00:03:45,256 --> 00:03:50,081
It can also help us relax if we deliberately tense muscles and then relax them slowly.

32
00:03:50,122 --> 00:03:52,645
Sounds strange, but it really works.

33
00:03:53,567 --> 00:03:57,110
It brings underlying tensions to the surface to where they can be released.

34
00:03:58,794 --> 00:04:03,294
But if you have any physical injury or weakness, you might just have to do this very gently.

35
00:04:03,697 --> 00:04:06,830
Or maybe just imagine yourself doing it, whatever is right for your body.

36
00:04:08,278 --> 00:04:14,145
We often hold underlying tension in the jaws, the forehead and all around the face and neck.

37
00:04:14,165 --> 00:04:27,461
So if you like squeezing all those muscles in the scalp, the forehead, the face, jaws, tongue, lips, throat, neck and holding all that tension for a few moments and then relaxing slowly.

38
00:04:27,502 --> 00:04:32,767
And you might even find yourself sighing as underlying tension is released on the out breath.

39
00:04:34,064 --> 00:04:43,396
Trying that again, if you like, squeezing all the muscles, holding the tension and releasing slowly, sighing all the tension away.

40
00:04:43,437 --> 00:04:55,634
You could also try that for the shoulders and hands, if you like, pulling the shoulders upwards, squeezing them in, tightening the hands into a fist.

41
00:04:55,654 --> 00:05:02,163
You might feel the whole upper body brace somewhat, holding that tension and then slowly releasing.

42
00:05:03,629 --> 00:05:13,420
repeating that if you like, bracing the shoulders, the arms, the hands, holding the tension, holding, and then releasing slowly.

43
00:05:16,267 --> 00:05:22,093
It can also help us relax by taking a deep breath and after a few moments releasing the air suddenly as a big sigh.

44
00:05:22,132 --> 00:05:33,923
And if you want to try that now, taking in a deep breath that fills all the chest and pushes the stomach high, holding for a few moments and then releasing completely.

45
00:05:33,963 --> 00:05:46,173
And you could try that again the next time the breath comes in, taking it in deeply, holding, holding and then sighing.

46
00:05:50,524 --> 00:05:52,708
So perhaps your body is relaxing now.

47
00:05:53,228 --> 00:05:54,750
But if not, that's not a problem.

48
00:05:55,471 --> 00:05:59,218
If you're feeling uptight, that's just some underlying emotion surfacing.

49
00:06:02,322 --> 00:06:06,149
Can you see this as an opportunity to get to know the experience of feeling uptight?

50
00:06:07,310 --> 00:06:10,314
Maybe reminding yourself now and again that it's okay to feel uptight.

51
00:06:10,896 --> 00:06:12,398
It's part of every human life.

52
00:06:15,026 --> 00:06:20,475
In Vipassana, our job is to get to know every aspect of life, so whatever comes our way is welcome.

53
00:06:25,041 --> 00:06:35,937
Body awareness is a really powerful aspect of Vipassana, so we'll do a short body scan, letting attention sink into each part of the body, from the crown of the head down to the toes.

54
00:06:37,117 --> 00:06:44,011
If you start feeling sleepy during the scan, then sitting upright, imagining that puppet string being pulled upwards towards the ceiling.

55
00:06:44,050 --> 00:06:47,517
Or if that doesn't help, opening your eyes for a while.

56
00:06:47,538 --> 00:06:51,766
Or standing up, whatever you need to do to remain awake.

57
00:06:54,480 --> 00:06:57,446
Starting at the crown of the head and the whole scalp area.

58
00:06:57,725 --> 00:06:59,069
How does that feel now?

59
00:06:59,108 --> 00:07:08,483
And letting your attention sink deep within the head and then surfacing towards your face as if you're coming up in your face from underneath the skin.

60
00:07:08,543 --> 00:07:12,230
Letting attention dwell in the forehead.

61
00:07:12,851 --> 00:07:14,553
Maybe it's frowning in concentration.

62
00:07:15,636 --> 00:07:17,298
If so, can it relax?

63
00:07:18,713 --> 00:07:25,841
Attention dwelling in the eyebrows and the eyes and the cheeks and the nose.

64
00:07:26,781 --> 00:07:29,564
You might feel how the in breath cools the nostrils slightly.

65
00:07:31,447 --> 00:07:33,309
Maybe flares them just a little too.

66
00:07:37,613 --> 00:07:39,896
What's the feeling of the out breath in the nostrils?

67
00:07:44,360 --> 00:07:46,223
And bringing attention into the upper jaw.

68
00:07:48,245 --> 00:07:49,305
And the lower jaw.

69
00:07:50,848 --> 00:07:53,670
And that hinge region behind the mouth where the jaws meet.

70
00:07:56,134 --> 00:08:01,319
If that area feels tight, then just circling the lower jaw for a few moments might loosen this.

71
00:08:04,043 --> 00:08:10,872
And your lips, you might try curling the corners of the lips upward slightly into a very slight subtle smile.

72
00:08:13,053 --> 00:08:15,416
Just seeing if that feels comfortable or pleasant.

73
00:08:18,771 --> 00:08:22,636
And inside the mouth, how do the teeth and gums feel?

74
00:08:22,696 --> 00:08:29,543
If the upper and lower teeth are locked together, see can they open slightly?

75
00:08:32,006 --> 00:08:35,730
Can the tongue relax, the tip just resting behind the front teeth?

76
00:08:38,995 --> 00:08:42,698
Can you follow sensations back down the tongue, down into the throat?

77
00:08:45,282 --> 00:08:46,803
How does the rest of the neck feel?

78
00:08:49,062 --> 00:08:56,993
Sometimes it's all a blank or a blur and sometimes there might be little tingling sensations in places when we bring our attention up close to the body like this.

79
00:08:58,716 --> 00:09:00,317
There's no right or wrong way to feel.

80
00:09:00,378 --> 00:09:03,081
There's just the truth of your present experience.

81
00:09:07,408 --> 00:09:09,029
Bringing attention into the shoulders.

82
00:09:09,931 --> 00:09:10,711
Are they tight?

83
00:09:11,413 --> 00:09:11,813
Tense?

84
00:09:13,015 --> 00:09:14,697
If so, can they relax a little?

85
00:09:16,432 --> 00:09:19,096
Tracing attention down the arms to the elbows.

86
00:09:20,856 --> 00:09:22,678
Is there a bony feeling to the elbows?

87
00:09:24,681 --> 00:09:27,442
It doesn't matter if you don't have words to describe sensations.

88
00:09:27,864 --> 00:09:30,525
Just resting the attention in the body is what's important.

89
00:09:32,849 --> 00:09:34,850
And the lower arms, how do they feel?

90
00:09:34,870 --> 00:09:39,215
Sometimes we don't feel any sensations in various parts of the body.

91
00:09:39,394 --> 00:09:40,275
That's fine too.

92
00:09:40,855 --> 00:09:42,398
Just noticing that blank feeling.

93
00:09:43,918 --> 00:09:45,039
And the wrists.

94
00:09:46,976 --> 00:09:47,798
and the hands.

95
00:09:49,700 --> 00:09:51,981
Do your hands feel warm in places, for example?

96
00:09:54,664 --> 00:09:56,447
Can you feel your hands touching one another?

97
00:09:58,989 --> 00:10:00,291
Or maybe they're touching your lap?

98
00:10:06,736 --> 00:10:13,203
And bringing the attention into the chest, tracing the back down from the shoulders to the waist.

99
00:10:16,778 --> 00:10:19,644
Can you feel the ribs rising and falling with each breath?

100
00:10:23,051 --> 00:10:25,235
Any feelings from deep inside the chest?

101
00:10:27,620 --> 00:10:31,287
Tingly feelings, strange feelings, maybe no feelings?

102
00:10:35,394 --> 00:10:36,778
Can you feel the heart beating?

103
00:10:40,268 --> 00:10:42,431
And if your mind wanders, no big deal.

104
00:10:42,471 --> 00:10:46,895
That's the nature of the mind, wanting something more interesting than just relaxing within the body.

105
00:10:48,778 --> 00:10:58,991
So not giving yourself a hard time about your mind wandering, but encouraging yourself to leave worries and plans and troubles and dreams and whatever aside for this time.

106
00:10:59,753 --> 00:11:04,258
And instead to spend a bit of time within yourself, getting to know your body a bit better.

107
00:11:04,317 --> 00:11:09,465
And bringing the attention to the waist area.

108
00:11:12,144 --> 00:11:19,471
You might feel the diaphragm, that big muscle underneath the chest as it plunges downwards into the abdomen on the in breath.

109
00:11:23,336 --> 00:11:25,958
You might feel how it floats up again as you breathe out.

110
00:11:30,182 --> 00:11:33,066
And can you feel how the tummy rises with each in breath?

111
00:11:37,210 --> 00:11:39,451
Falls back down again on the out breath.

112
00:11:42,789 --> 00:11:44,772
or deep within the abdomen pelvis.

113
00:11:45,011 --> 00:11:46,193
Are there any sensations?

114
00:11:49,878 --> 00:11:54,562
Can you feel the internal organs being pushed downwards towards the pelvic floor as you breathe in?

115
00:11:54,582 --> 00:11:59,327
And relaxing back again as you breathe out.

116
00:12:04,572 --> 00:12:06,115
How does the lower back feel?

117
00:12:09,470 --> 00:12:17,399
And if there is discomfort here or anywhere else in the body, see and can you relax around the discomfort, feeling it just as it is.

118
00:12:21,345 --> 00:12:23,307
Bringing attention to the genital area.

119
00:12:24,908 --> 00:12:27,211
To the hips left and right.

120
00:12:29,455 --> 00:12:38,346
And letting attention drift along the thighs all the way from the hips and right throughout that large muscle mass down to the knees.

121
00:12:40,333 --> 00:12:41,836
How do the lower legs feel?

122
00:12:41,875 --> 00:12:45,741
Are there touching sensations in places?

123
00:12:46,563 --> 00:12:49,567
Perhaps the legs touching one another or touching clothing.

124
00:12:50,910 --> 00:12:52,253
Itching sensations maybe.

125
00:12:52,312 --> 00:12:56,139
Noticing how your ankles feel.

126
00:12:56,158 --> 00:12:58,522
And your feet.

127
00:12:59,624 --> 00:13:00,445
The heels.

128
00:13:01,567 --> 00:13:03,190
Through the sole of the foot.

129
00:13:04,270 --> 00:13:05,533
The upper part of the foot.

130
00:13:06,936 --> 00:13:08,518
And right down to the toes.

131
00:13:10,625 --> 00:13:16,817
the big toes, the little toes, and all those toes in between.

132
00:13:16,837 --> 00:13:31,366
And having visited every part of the body, bringing your attention to the wave of breath that swells the trunk of the body as it passes through.

133
00:13:39,363 --> 00:13:44,548
And just breathing naturally, not trying to breathe slowly or deeply or any way special.

134
00:13:48,552 --> 00:13:52,357
All we're doing is getting to know the physical sensations associated with breathing.

135
00:13:54,379 --> 00:13:57,423
So can you feel the tummy rising and falling as you breathe?

136
00:14:03,269 --> 00:14:08,796
Or it might be that you feel the breath in the chest, the rising and falling of the chest every time you breathe.

137
00:14:17,315 --> 00:14:26,292
If you can't feel any movements, then you might place a hand on your tummy or your chest and that can focus attention there so you feel the movement more clearly.

138
00:14:33,426 --> 00:14:39,457
So just spending a few moments now finding which area of the body is moving most obviously as you breathe.

139
00:14:50,625 --> 00:14:56,594
And once you've settled on an area, best keep your attention there rather than moving it around from place to place.

140
00:14:59,697 --> 00:15:04,224
And if you've already trained yourself to concentrate by feeling the breath at the nostrils, that's fine.

141
00:15:05,125 --> 00:15:10,052
But for the Mahasi meditation practice, it is recommended to feel the breath deep within the trunk of the body.

142
00:15:24,072 --> 00:15:31,905
It's also recommended to make a mental note of whatever you're experiencing as this helps to steady the mind and strengthens awareness.

143
00:15:33,708 --> 00:15:39,580
So as you feel a rising movement, you could be noting to yourself, rising, rising.

144
00:15:41,903 --> 00:15:45,591
And as you feel a falling movement, falling, falling.

145
00:15:49,368 --> 00:15:59,942
If you're following the breath of the nostrils, then noting in, in and out, out as you feel the breath coming in and out of the body.

146
00:15:59,981 --> 00:16:12,337
These noting words can be very soft, almost like a footnote, because it's the physical sensation we're interested in.

147
00:16:15,254 --> 00:16:25,273
So if the noting word seems really loud in your mind, kind of obscuring the feeling of breathing, then you could deliberately soften that.

148
00:16:31,183 --> 00:16:36,333
It's almost like a feather just brushing against the physical feelings of breathing.

149
00:16:45,038 --> 00:16:48,705
If there's a gap between breaths, then you could bring attention to some touch point.

150
00:16:49,287 --> 00:16:53,254
For example, the hands touching one another or the buttocks touching the cushion.

151
00:16:55,298 --> 00:17:00,229
And noting touching, touching until you next feel a movement due to breathing.

152
00:17:16,949 --> 00:17:32,545
So you're just following the physical sensations due to breathing and noting in your mind rising, falling, touching, rising and so on, following the pace of your breath.

153
00:17:56,217 --> 00:18:03,055
If your mind wanders, then as soon as you notice this, you could be curious about the general direction of your thought.

154
00:18:03,075 --> 00:18:06,483
For example, planning or dreaming or worrying.

155
00:18:07,747 --> 00:18:12,318
And then making a gentle note of this before inviting your attention back to the feeling of breathing.

156
00:18:15,556 --> 00:18:17,779
Not giving yourself a hard time for wandering.

157
00:18:18,340 --> 00:18:22,487
We're not making an enemy out of the wandering mind, but getting to know it as well.

158
00:18:22,547 --> 00:18:26,232
Becoming more aware of the general direction you tend to wander in.

159
00:18:26,292 --> 00:18:31,883
That can bring us to a deeper self-awareness.

160
00:18:32,903 --> 00:18:40,737
So perhaps you could cultivate an amused curiosity about the direction of your wandering mind, rather than a sense of exasperation towards it.

161
00:18:43,737 --> 00:18:51,924
and having noted planning or worrying or whatever, then bringing your attention back into the body and the feeling of breathing.

162
00:18:57,067 --> 00:18:59,732
And sometimes you might not remember what you were thinking about.

163
00:18:59,752 --> 00:19:04,762
No need to go racking your brain trying to work out whether it was a plan or a worry or whatever.

164
00:19:05,324 --> 00:19:14,622
But just coming back then to the feeling of breathing, rising, falling, touching and so on.

165
00:19:50,343 --> 00:20:04,001
If you're feeling sleepy, then sitting upright, giving a little tug at that puppet string, or opening your eyes, letting in the light, or standing for a while, whatever you need to do to remain awake.

166
00:20:06,184 --> 00:20:08,308
But we're not making an enemy out of sleepiness.

167
00:20:08,989 --> 00:20:11,512
Our job here is to get to know every human state.

168
00:20:13,256 --> 00:20:15,558
So we're interested in the feeling of sleepiness.

169
00:20:16,619 --> 00:20:18,403
Does it feel pleasant, for example?

170
00:20:19,023 --> 00:20:19,944
Do you like that feeling?

171
00:20:22,861 --> 00:20:23,903
How does your body feel?

172
00:20:23,923 --> 00:20:26,707
Is it heavy in places?

173
00:20:30,252 --> 00:20:32,537
And your mind, how does your mind feel?

174
00:20:32,576 --> 00:20:34,720
Does it feel a bit dull?

175
00:20:34,779 --> 00:20:46,859
Seeing can you just stay awake and alert enough to get to know the moment to moment feeling of sleepiness.

176
00:21:24,032 --> 00:21:31,468
If your mind is wandering a lot, then it's best to keep returning to the breath and let that rhythmic wave of breathing calm down the busy mind.

177
00:21:34,374 --> 00:21:42,430
But if your attention has steadied and you feel interested in your present experience, then letting your attention be drawn to whatever attracts it.

178
00:21:44,182 --> 00:21:46,945
Maybe an itching feeling in the body draws attention.

179
00:21:47,006 --> 00:21:56,721
If so, letting that come to the forefront and noting itching, itching while you let all those physical sensations be felt.

180
00:21:59,846 --> 00:22:01,869
Or maybe some sound takes your attention.

181
00:22:02,270 --> 00:22:09,582
So noting hearing, hearing as you listen to the detail of the sound, all its notes and rhythms.

182
00:22:11,553 --> 00:22:16,223
Whatever draws attention, letting yourself zoom into this experience to feel it fully.

183
00:22:16,263 --> 00:22:29,375
And if it fades away, if it doesn't take your attention anymore, and if nothing else particularly draws attention, then going back again to the rising falling movements of breathing.

184
00:22:58,364 --> 00:23:13,538
If you notice yourself reacting, for example, disliking the feeling of itching, liking some sounds, disliking others, then noting these reactions, liking, liking or disliking, disliking.

185
00:23:15,964 --> 00:23:21,717
You might notice how these reactions can sometimes set up a whole train of thoughts and internal arguments.

186
00:23:22,919 --> 00:23:30,615
Keeping track of these as best you can, noting thinking, thinking or arguing, arguing to deepen the acknowledgement.

187
00:24:49,115 --> 00:25:00,229
If you notice yourself feeling calm and peaceful, then noting this calm, calm or peaceful, peaceful for as long as it holds attention.

188
00:25:04,095 --> 00:25:12,685
And if you're getting stiff or in pain, then bringing this centre stage and noting stiff, stiff or pain, pain.

189
00:25:14,688 --> 00:25:17,551
Bringing attention right into the heart of the discomfort.

190
00:25:19,237 --> 00:25:23,622
Is it aching or burning or pressing?

191
00:25:23,642 --> 00:25:27,267
Or maybe there are no words to describe it.

192
00:25:30,631 --> 00:25:32,634
Is it all concentrated in a point?

193
00:25:34,175 --> 00:25:36,178
Or is it a line of discomfort?

194
00:25:37,779 --> 00:25:39,041
Or a general area?

195
00:25:42,025 --> 00:25:43,446
How far does it extend?

196
00:25:46,691 --> 00:25:48,113
Resting attention there

197
00:25:49,392 --> 00:25:51,155
right in the heart of the discomfort.

198
00:25:53,601 --> 00:26:01,135
Also noticing any mental reactions, for example irritation, anxiety, wishing the pain would go away.

199
00:26:01,175 --> 00:26:08,852
Again, noting all these, allowing your body and mind to be just as they are.

200
00:26:14,231 --> 00:26:18,357
And sometimes the mental reactions are more subtle, harder to notice.

201
00:26:19,380 --> 00:26:27,132
So it can help to switch attention from the painful area to a more comfortable area for a while and then back to the painful area again.

202
00:26:27,192 --> 00:26:32,140
This can help us feel how the mind reacts to pain.

203
00:26:39,275 --> 00:26:41,080
but we're not trying to torture ourselves.

204
00:26:41,563 --> 00:26:45,536
So if you feel it's all too much, then moving mindfully to relieve the discomfort.

205
00:26:46,358 --> 00:26:49,790
Noticing how your mood might lift as your body gets comfortable again.

206
00:27:31,232 --> 00:27:35,344
Letting whatever calls attention to become center stage in our awareness.

207
00:27:36,507 --> 00:27:41,579
And if nothing particularly calls attention, then going back to rising, falling again.

208
00:28:39,644 --> 00:28:50,094
If you notice yourself trying hard to meditate to get it right, you can note trying, trying and become curious about the feeling of trying.

209
00:28:56,259 --> 00:29:08,352
If it's the opposite and you're feeling lazy, not wanting to bother noticing anything, you could note lazy, lazy and allow that experience to take centre stage for as long as it lasts.

210
00:29:11,925 --> 00:29:14,411
Letting yourself feel just exactly as you do feel.

211
00:29:14,451 --> 00:29:31,082
And if whatever you're noting seems to fade away, stops calling attention, and if nothing else takes attention, then you can go back to the rising, falling feelings again.

212
00:30:47,928 --> 00:30:54,499
If you find your mind is wandering, then the very moment of waking up and noticing this is a very rich opportunity.

213
00:30:54,558 --> 00:30:57,143
How does that wake up feel?

214
00:30:57,163 --> 00:30:59,467
Is it a slight startle?

215
00:30:59,487 --> 00:31:03,794
Or maybe a gentle sliding back into awareness?

216
00:31:06,878 --> 00:31:12,567
Sometimes we can still feel the emotion that was driving the wandering mind or the startle reaction.

217
00:31:14,843 --> 00:31:36,243
If so, see can you allow these feelings to become centre stage for as long as they last, using whatever noting words help acknowledge the experience, like dreaming, dreaming, if you still have the feeling of daydreaming, or worrying, worrying, if you can still sense that feeling of being worried.

218
00:31:44,137 --> 00:31:46,883
And getting to know these feelings in our bodies as well.

219
00:31:46,942 --> 00:31:55,135
Worrying can sometimes tense the forehead or the jaws, for example, maybe the chest, the stomach.

220
00:31:57,540 --> 00:32:03,750
Or that feeling of dreaming might have an effect, maybe in the chest again, maybe warm, pleasant feelings this time.

221
00:32:05,012 --> 00:32:09,740
Just see if you can notice any part of the body that's associated with the underlying emotion.

222
00:32:13,113 --> 00:32:17,156
Can you let your attention dwell there to acknowledge the experience more deeply?

223
00:32:17,196 --> 00:32:33,153
And then, if the experience fades away, no longer calls attention, and if nothing else particularly calls attention, then going back to the feelings of the breath again.

224
00:32:33,192 --> 00:32:39,880
Rising, falling, touching, and so on.

225
00:33:46,042 --> 00:34:01,301
If you're feeling sleepy, then straightening the back, giving a little tug at that puppet string, opening your eyes or standing or whatever you find helps you to stay awake and alert enough to get to know the feeling of sleepiness.

226
00:35:02,014 --> 00:35:05,780
If any emotion arises, see if you can experience this fully.

227
00:35:05,820 --> 00:35:14,574
So whether it's a pleasant emotion, like maybe you're feeling happy or calm, just noting these.

228
00:35:14,695 --> 00:35:18,400
So happy, happy, calm, calm.

229
00:35:20,644 --> 00:35:25,271
Or if it's an unpleasant state, like maybe you're feeling irritable or impatient.

230
00:35:25,876 --> 00:35:27,237
Again, can you note this?

231
00:35:27,297 --> 00:35:32,344
Irritable, irritable, impatient, impatient.

232
00:35:35,608 --> 00:35:37,731
Being curious about the body as well.

233
00:35:37,791 --> 00:35:40,213
Every emotion has some effect on the body.

234
00:35:42,476 --> 00:35:47,023
So if there's any part of the body calling attention, just letting your attention rest there.

235
00:35:47,983 --> 00:35:50,887
And that'll help you to acknowledge the emotion at a deeper level.

236
00:35:56,538 --> 00:36:03,206
And if the emotion fades away and nothing else particularly takes your attention, always going back to the rising falling again.

237
00:37:24,608 --> 00:37:49,079
If your mind is wandering, then being curious about the feeling of waking up and any remaining feeling of the emotion that might have been driving the wandering mind, the feeling of worrying, the feeling of planning, the feeling of dreaming, perhaps just allowing those feelings to be fully felt in mind and body for as long as they last.

238
00:38:16,380 --> 00:38:29,641
If your mind is very restless, hopping from one thought to the next, then noting restless, restless, as you bring attention into the body as well, especially to any areas of tension, relaxing whatever is possible.

239
00:38:29,681 --> 00:38:36,853
And perhaps letting the rhythmic wave of breathing provide a calm background to the experience of restlessness.

240
00:39:54,880 --> 00:39:59,327
Allowing yourself to be just as you are, to feel your body and your emotions fully.

241
00:39:59,367 --> 00:40:07,880
Not trying to interfere and fix what you don't like, but allowing whatever experience you're going through to be felt just exactly as it is.

242
00:40:07,940 --> 00:40:21,039
So if you feel yourself struggling or judging that you're doing something wrong, that you shouldn't be feeling like this, noting these experiences as struggling, judging and so on.

243
00:40:22,353 --> 00:40:32,822
bringing attention right into the body, especially into the heart area there at the center of the chest to feel how the heart is responding to whatever you're going through.

244
00:40:41,989 --> 00:40:46,873
These are actually valuable experiences teaching us about the true nature of human suffering.

245
00:40:47,994 --> 00:40:51,398
So see, can you allow yourself to relax and feel them fully?

246
00:40:53,452 --> 00:40:58,920
If you can, you may get a glimpse of the four noble truths, the essence of the Buddha's teaching.

247
00:41:02,784 --> 00:41:15,242
If you're struggling against physical pain, for example, wishing it would go away and let you meditate in peace, then this provides an experience of the first truth, that there is dukkha, or difficulty, in life.

248
00:41:17,027 --> 00:41:19,972
The Buddha's injunction is to fully understand dukkha.

249
00:41:21,153 --> 00:41:29,407
And for this reason we allow ourselves to feel the physical pain and any reactions such as the sense of struggling somehow, trying to relax perhaps.

250
00:41:31,891 --> 00:41:36,538
Noticing all this, we sometimes just tire of the struggling, even just for a moment.

251
00:41:37,750 --> 00:41:47,188
To our great surprise we find that, although the pain is still there, we feel okay for that moment, relaxed and at peace even in the midst of the pain.

252
00:41:49,693 --> 00:41:53,681
We realize that it was the struggling against pain that was causing the misery.

253
00:41:55,766 --> 00:41:59,032
In this moment we're experiencing the second noble truth.

254
00:41:59,670 --> 00:42:10,043
That dukkha is caused not by the circumstances we find ourselves in, but by our reactions of trying to get rid of what we dislike and to hold on to what we do like.

255
00:42:14,369 --> 00:42:21,476
That feeling of ease we get when we stop struggling is a glimpse of the third noble truth, that dukkha does stop.

256
00:42:24,780 --> 00:42:37,860
When we reflect on all this, we realize we found a method to allow dukkha to come to its natural end by letting go of our instinctive reactions of desire to hold on to what we like and to get rid of what we dislike.

257
00:42:41,085 --> 00:42:45,692
So we found for ourselves the fourth noble truth, the way to the end of all suffering.

258
00:42:53,619 --> 00:42:55,682
This is the great value of Vipassana.

259
00:42:56,684 --> 00:43:05,717
It teaches us to see things just as they really are and thereby to come to the end of the difficulties associated with the human condition.

260
00:43:08,862 --> 00:43:16,253
So let's continue with the practice in silence for a few more moments, letting each experience teach us the way to the end of suffering.

261
00:44:31,393 --> 00:44:36,021
And bringing our meditation practice to a close with a good wish for ourselves and others.

262
00:44:38,784 --> 00:44:45,454
May I be safe and well and happy and enjoy a fulfilling, fruitful life.

263
00:44:52,463 --> 00:44:55,849
Extending those good wishes to close family and friends.

264
00:44:59,659 --> 00:45:06,092
May you be safe and well and happy and enjoy fulfilling and fruitful lives.

265
00:45:12,264 --> 00:45:20,199
Extending those good wishes further to our neighbours, colleagues at work, a wider circle of friends.

266
00:45:26,659 --> 00:45:33,427
May you be safe, well and happy and enjoy fulfilling and fruitful lives.

267
00:45:41,077 --> 00:45:51,789
And finally, extending those good wishes throughout the world to all people on Earth, if you like, including animals, plants, even the physical Earth itself.

268
00:45:58,012 --> 00:46:04,344
May all be safe and well and happy and enjoy fulfilling and fruitful lives.

